article.description:
Lisa Leslie collected 19 points and a career-high 17 rebounds as the host Los Angeles Sparks posted a 69-55
victory over the Minnesota Lynx on Friday night.
article.headline: Smith becomes 4th WNBA player score 3,000
article.linkText: Leslie's double-double paces L.A. over Lynx
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Katie Smith's scoring milestone wasn't enough
for the Minnesota Lynx.

Smith scored 18 points for Minnesota to become the fourth WNBA
player to score 3,000, but Lisa Leslie's 19 points and 17 rebounds
helped Los Angeles beat the Lynx 69-55 Friday night.

"It's not something you're thinking about or aiming for,"
Smith said. "If you do what you're supposed to do and play well,
stuff like that will happen."

Leslie added five assists and four blocks for the Sparks, who
moved into a tie with Houston for second place in the Western
Conference. Both are a game behind Seattle.

"We just really started to get into a good rhythm," Leslie
said. "Having six new players, it's about getting that rhythm,
feeling like were not losing anything."

Smith, who also played for the American Basketball League's
Columbus Quest, holds the career record with 4,443 points. Los
Angeles' Lisa Leslie, Houston's Tina Thompson and Charlotte's
Andrea Stinson also have reached the milestone.

Minnesota's Nicole Ohlde added 12 points and tied a season-high
with 10 rebounds.

The Lynx took a 25-22 lead with 9:14 left in the first half on
Helen Darling's 3-pointer, but were outscored 13-0 over the next
8:24.

The Lynx narrowed the deficit to 42-38 with 16:30 to play but
Nikki Teasley scored five points in a 7-0 run that extended the
Sparks' lead to 49-38 with 15:05 remaining.

Minnesota scored just 10 points, and only one basket, in the
final 10 minutes and shot 31 percent for the game.
